6.10 Assessing Match Quality
Matching should not end after estimating the treatment effect. A crucial step is checking whether matching actually improved balance between treated and untreated units.
The goal is not to predict treatment as well as possible. The goal is to make the distribution of covariates similar across groups after matching.
Common diagnostics include:

comparing covariate means before and after matching;
checking standardized mean differences;
inspecting the distribution of the propensity score;
verifying common support;
reporting how many treated units are unmatched or discarded.

A matching estimator is credible only if treated and matched control units are sufficiently similar in pre-treatment characteristics.






NoteBalance before effects



Before interpreting the estimated treatment effect, check whether matching has balanced the covariates.
If balance remains poor, the matched comparison group is not a credible counterfactual.

9.8 Graphical Evidence
RDD is often presented using a figure that plots the outcome against the running variable. The graph usually shows:

binned averages of the outcome;
the cutoff;
fitted curves or lines on each side of the cutoff;
the estimated jump at the threshold.

The visual evidence is not a substitute for formal estimation, but it is important. A convincing RDD should show a clear discontinuity in the outcome at the cutoff, without similar discontinuities in pre-treatment covariates.

9.12 Main Strengths and Limitations
RDD is powerful because it can provide credible causal evidence in settings where treatment assignment is not randomized but follows a known rule.
Its strengths are:

transparent identification;
strong visual intuition;
limited extrapolation;
comparison of units close to the treatment threshold.

Its limitations are:

the effect is local to the cutoff;
the design requires a clear and known threshold;
manipulation of the running variable can invalidate the design;
results may be sensitive to bandwidth choice;
spatial RDD may confound the policy of interest with other boundary changes.







WarningLocal does not mean weak



RDD estimates are often highly credible near the cutoff.
The price of this credibility is that the estimate may not generalize to units far from the threshold.

10.13 What to Report
A credible IV analysis should report:

the institutional or theoretical argument for the instrument;
the first-stage relationship between the instrument and treatment;
the first-stage F-statistic or other weak-instrument diagnostics;
the reduced-form effect of the instrument on the outcome;
the 2SLS estimate;
the set of covariates included in both stages;
the standard error procedure;
a discussion of the exclusion restriction;
an interpretation of the complier population when the LATE framework applies.







TipIV reporting logic



Do not report only the second-stage estimate.
An IV design is credible only if the first stage, reduced form, exclusion restriction, and target population are all clearly discussed.

10.14 Strengths and Limitations
Instrumental variables are powerful because they can address unobserved confounding. Unlike matching or regression adjustment, IV methods do not require all confounders to be observed. Instead, they require a valid source of exogenous variation in treatment.
However, this strength comes at a cost. The exclusion restriction is often difficult to justify, weak instruments can make estimates unreliable, and the estimated effect is often local to compliers.
The main strengths of IV are:

it can address selection on unobservables;
it can exploit natural experiments or institutional rules;
it provides a clear design-based logic when a strong instrument is available.

The main limitations are:

the exclusion restriction is not directly testable;
weak instruments can produce misleading estimates;
the estimand may be a LATE rather than an ATE or ATT;
different instruments may identify different treatment effects;
interpretation depends heavily on the institutional context.

11.8 When SCM is useful
SCM is especially useful for evaluating aggregate interventions affecting one or a small number of aggregate units, such as countries, regions, cities, or municipalities.
It is most appropriate when:

there is one treated unit, or a small number of treated units;
a credible donor pool of untreated units is available;
data are available for several periods before treatment, so that the credibility of the synthetic unit as a valid counterfactual can be assessed;
data are available for several periods after treatment, so that the impact of the treatment can be evaluated some time after its onset;
the synthetic control reproduces the treated unit well before the intervention.

SCM is less convincing when the treated unit is too different from all units in the donor pool, when the pre-treatment period is very short, or when the synthetic control fails to closely approximate the treated unit before treatment.







TipPractical implication



SCM should only be used when the synthetic control provides a credible approximation of the treated unit before the intervention.
If the pre-treatment fit is poor, the post-treatment gap is difficult to interpret as a causal effect.
